<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / People: Engineering a future at Simon
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It's goodbye for a week to my spouse,
For the pleasures of yachting at Cowes.
I'll be hosting all day
At our corporate chalet
And each night I'm obliged to carouse.
Two years after penning this winning entry for a competition in The
Independent, the author is moving to a company where severe belt-tightening
rather than carousing will be the order of the day.
Maurice Dixson, who in addition to being a keen limerick writer, has had a
distinguished career with British Aerospace (owners of the above-mentioned
corporate chalet) and GEC, is moving to Simon Engineering as its new chief
executive, in succession to Brian Kemp.
Michael Davies, installed as chairman only last month, has lost no time in
recruiting a new executive boss who has, as Davies puts it, 'the opportunity
to restore the company's fortunes in a way that Brian perhaps doesn't'
In May the company warned of a loss for the first half of this year which
would then put it in breach of one of its banking covenants.
In addition, some institutional shareholders are understood to have been
unhappy that Kemp, 49, who was awarded a seven per cent pay increase last
year despite a 71 per cent fall in profits. Others blamed him for the
unsuccessful diversification into environmental businesses.
'Simon is a very famous name; one of the attractions of the job is to
restore it to where it ought to be, in the forefront of British engineering'
says Dixson, adding that he will be going in with his 'eyes open'.
Dixson, 51, who in the mid 1960s did an Oxford doctoral thesis in the
politics and economics of defence procurement, has been on the board of GEC
for the past three and a half years, as group managing director in charge of
the electronic metrology and components groups.
Prior to that he had been at BAe, latterly as managing director of the
commercial aircraft side and before that as chief executive of Royal
Ordnance.
His name, together with that of Dudley Eustace, now finance director of
Philips, was at one time in the ring as a possible successor to former
chairman Sir Raymond Lygo.
He says there will be 'a fairly short-term' handover period with Kemp,
followed by 'a longer period of consultation when he will be at the end of a
telephone.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Simon Engineering.
</CO>
<XX>
