<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / GEC 'had agreed to buy' Swan Hunter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GEC HAD agreed to buy Swan Hunter, the Tyneside shipbuilder, before it went
into receivership in May.
But the draft agreement signed between the two companies lapsed when Swans
failed to win a contract to build a helicopter carrier for the Royal Navy,
Price Waterhouse, Swans' receiver, said yesterday. The contract went instead
to VSEL of Barrow-in-Furness, Cumbria. After a fruitless 24-hour search for
another backer, Swan Hunter called in the receiver.
Since then 19 interested parties have contacted Price Waterhouse, which
wants to sell Swan Hunter as a going concern. It said talks were continuing
but details were commercially sensitive.
In its first report to creditors, Price Waterhouse also confirmed that
unsecured creditors of the company were 'unlikely' to salvage anything from
its crash.
A creditors' meeting in Newcastle upon Tyne heard that the company had debts
of more than Pounds 40m. Its assets had a book value of Pounds 39.2m, but a
sale would realise only Pounds 6.3m, said the receiver.
Some Pounds 27.7m is owed to secured creditors - Pounds 12.2m in loans from
Lloyds Bank and Pounds 15.5m owed to the General Surety and Guarantee
Company. The Pounds 15.5m is the face value of bonds provided to the
Ministry of Defence to ensure the completion of three Type 23 frigates.
The receiver said Pounds 5.2m owed to preferential creditors in tax and
national insurance, holiday pay, wages and pension contributions would be
paid.
Swan Hunter's management accounts showed a Pounds 1.6m profit in the first
six months of the year, reversing two years of losses totalling Pounds 26m.
The shipyard's financial problems had been cited by Mr Jonathan Aitken,
defence procurement minister, as contributing to the company's failure to
put forward a low enough bid for the contract. At the time Swan Hunter went
into receivership, 90 per cent of its business was with the Ministry of
Defence for the construction of the three Type 23 frigates.
VSEL has said it wants to take over these contracts and finish the work on
Tyneside. The receiver indicated this would not satisfy the desire to sell
Swans as a going concern.
</TEXT>
