<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / Contest for EC funds considered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT may force local authorities and local economic development
agencies to enter formal competitions for European Community regional funds.
The Department of Trade Industry said yesterday it was considering such a
scheme for the funds, which are to help areas of industrial decline and
urban deprivation, but added: 'It is just an idea that's being looked at, at
the moment.'
The idea, however, has been discussed for several months and owes its
origins to City Challenge, a competition devised in 1991 by Mr Michael
Heseltine, when he was environment secretary.
Local private- and public-sector partnerships were invited to bid for the
funding of regeneration programmes concentrated on a specific urban area.
Any new competition would be for what the EC calls Objective Two funds,
flowing from Brussels between 1994 and 1996.
Although local authorities have already started lobbying Whitehall in the
hope of obtaining support for inclusion on the map of eligible areas, the
European Commission will not finalise the map until the autumn.
Between 1989 and 1993 the EC provided Pounds 229m of Objective Two funding
for the UK. Local authorities made bids for use of the money through the UK
government but bids did not always reach the total sum available from
Brussels.
This was because the government, to the anger of the Commission, would
simply deduct a sum equivalent to the EC funding from its planned grants to
a local authority.
The government now has greater scope to stage a competition because it has
agreed to abide by the EC rules of providing funding to match any EC grant.
This makes the funding more attractive to local authorities.
Past practice suggests that government rules for any competition are likely
to lay emphasis on, and give funding preference to, partnerships between the
private and the public sector. But the rules will have to be approved by the
Commission.
The DTI will handle the negotiations with the Commission but the Department
of Environment will administer any competition and disburse the funds for
the EC.
</TEXT>
