FT  11 AUG 93 / England's first three 'community forests' given the go-ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government has given the go-ahead for England's first three 'community
forests', which are designed to improve the landscape and give town dwellers
access to leisure activities on their doorstep.
The forests are a joint initiative by the Countryside Commission and the
Forestry Commission, which have been working with local authorities.
The forests will be called Thames Chase, near South Ockenden, east of
London; the Forest of Mercia, in south Staffordshire; and the Great North
Forest, in Tyne and Wear.
The government has approved the Countryside Commission's business plans for
the forests. Some planting has begun and grants will be available from the
Forestry Commission and the Ministry of Agriculture.
It could take 40 years for the forests, which will be a blend of woodland,
farmland and open space, to be established fully. Nine more forests are
under consideration.
