<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / Cross-border alliances between banks fell last year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE number of cross-border alliances formed between European banks and
financial services companies fell last year as the French banks, which have
been the most active in such deals, were affected by recession, John Gapper
writes.
A bulletin article analysing 247 cross-border financial alliances over the
past six years finds that 74 partnerships were initiated by French companies
against 36 by UK companies and 35 by German.
The most common form of alliance came from large companies buying stakes in
smaller ones. Outright acquisitions or the purchase of a majority stake
accounted for 46 per cent of deals, and joint ventures only 8 per cent.
German and UK institutions favoured buying entire business units or majority
stakes, while most French and Italian ventures took minority stakes.
Last year French alliances dropped from 23 to three. Deals by UK companies
fell to two from a consistent rate of between six and nine a year.
</TEXT>
