<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / Valleys welcome falls on deaf ears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY ENGLISH company executives remain unconvinced by male-voice choirs
pledging a warm welcome in the hillsides and valleys of Wales.
A survey of 500 company directors based in the south of England shows that
more than a third believe that the Welsh are anything but welcoming to
people moving in from over the border.
The survey, by Cardiff-based SRD Consultants, suggests that while south
Wales has been successful in attracting inward investment from overseas it
has yet to convince many 'foreigners' closer to home to set up shop in the
principality.
A quarter of English company executives said that their children would be
disadvantaged by being brought up in Wales. More than half said the range of
facilities available to families were below the standards in England.
'It is just such considerations that could lead to Wales losing its
competitive edge in company relocation and new investment decisions,' said
Mr John Smith, former Labour MP for Vale of Glamorgan, and campaign manager
for Gwent Image, a partnership between the public and private sectors. Gwent
Image is dedicated to sweeping away the old image of coal-black terraces and
endless tips and promoting a more positive, modern image.
He said that although many English businesspeople had crossed the border and
happily settled, perceptions of remoteness, run-down industries and
unfriendly communities prevented many others from joining them.
Mr Smith added: 'We are making great strides in remedying the first two
factors. People are beginning to appreciate that industrial sites have been
cleaned up and that south Wales is just across the Severn Bridge.
'But we have to work on convincing potential business investors that the
Welsh are friendly and welcoming.'
Gwent is about to begin a promotional campaign aimed at attracting
investment. More than 1m letters will be sent to potential immigrants. It
could be an uphill struggle - 42 per cent of businesspeople surveyed did not
even know where Gwent is.
</TEXT>
