<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / Warning on radio advert revenue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMMERCIAL RADIO needs to increase total advertising revenue by at least 50
per cent to meet the planned increase in the number of new stations,
according to a report from consultants Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
In order to fund the growing number of commercial radio services, the report
says, the sector will need to achieve a 3 per cent share of total
advertising revenue. In 1992, it brought in Pounds 140m in advertising
revenue - an overall share of 2 per cent.
It says there will be 180 commercial local and regional services as well as
three national stations by 1996.
The report adds: 'It is essential to the future profitability of independent
radio that the increase in listening share is accompanied by an increase in
revenue share. Unless this is accomplished the industry will be in trouble
by 1996.'
The radio industry needs to overturn indifference from advertising agencies
towards the medium.
Coopers believes this will be helped by the growth in audiences, by the
launch of national stations, by advertising sales packages such as National
Network Radio and by the Radio Advertising Bureau which is promoting
commercial radio.
Mr George Eccles of Coopers &amp; Lybrand said yesterday he believed the 3 per
cent share was possible, and was 'essential to the future profitability of
independent radio'.
Independent Radio: The Route To Survival. Heidi Rowe, Coopers &amp; Lybrand, 1
Embankment Place, London WC2N 6NN. Pounds 50.
</TEXT>
