<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / Clampdown on dole fraud saves government Pounds 44.7m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CLAMPDOWN on dole fraud last year netted the government Pounds 44.7m, the
Department of Employment said yesterday.
In 250,000-plus investigations during 1992-93, more than 61,100 people
withdrew their benefit claims, while 2,602 claimants and 55 employers were
prosecuted.
In one operation at London's Heathrow airport more than 100 minicab drivers
were caught, while 550 seaside workers in Wales withdrew claims after an
investigation.
The department says it is identifying more cases of collusion by employers,
who encourage workers to claim unemployment benefits while paying low wages.
The practice is particularly prevalent in textiles, construction and
agriculture.
Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, said: 'This behaviour gives
unscrupulous employers an unfair advantage over their competitors. Their
workforce claim benefits, and so are paid lower wages. It is unfair
competition, an example of how the black economy corrodes the fabric of our
society.'
The Department of Employment has estimated that about 8 per cent of
unemployment claims may be fraudulent, amounting to some Pounds 500m. This
year it has no financial target for savings but aims to have 63,000 claims
withdrawn by the end of the financial year.
Last year's operations, which grossed Pounds 71.1m, cost the department
Pounds 26.4m. It says it saved Pounds 2.69 for every Pounds 1 invested.
'Travelling' fraud, whereby claimants sign on in one area and work in
another, is on the increase, according to the department.
</TEXT>
