<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / Welsh companies at risk as mail strike continues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY SMALL companies in south Wales are on the verge of closure and
bankruptcy as a result of the eight-day Royal Mail dispute in Cardiff, which
has led to well over 1m letters being undelivered.
'Some businesses are at a virtual standstill,' said Mr Graham Hall, chief
executive of the Wales Chamber of Commerce and Industry, last night. 'Cash
flow is affected, they are not getting orders or cheques in their post and
in some cases legal action will be brought by suppliers outside south Wales
who are unaware that their letters are being held up by the strike.'
Mr Hall said that the chamber was trying to press the Post Office and the
Union of Communication Workers to end the strike. 'Businesses outside the
area are not aware of the dispute and are still sending letters to Cardiff
companies and do not realise why they are not getting any response.'
He warned that courier services and transport companies were 'extremely
busy' as a result of the strike and the sale of fax machines was soaring.
'When the dispute is over companies will not all revert to using the post,'
he said.
Further talks are to be held today to try to end the strike, over new work
rosters. After a four-hour meeting yesterday, a union executive said that
negotiations had 'reached a critical stage' and called on the management to
honour an agreement to apply new fixed rosters 'in the fairest possible
way'.
The 900 striking workers will be ballotted on a peace formula when one
emerges. But prolonged talks between the Post Office and union national
officials have so far failed to secure agreement.
</TEXT>
