<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / World Trade News: Ricoh in Chinese fax venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RICOH, the Japanese office equipment company, has formed a Dollars 15m joint
venture to produce facsimile machines in Shanghai, joining the rush of
Japanese companies seeking, in lower-cost China, refuge from yen
appreciation.
The venture, designed to produce machines for sale in China and for export
in the Asian region, is expected to have an output of 40,000 units per month
when a planned factory is completed in 1996.
Ricoh has a 49.5 per cent stake, while Shanghai Facsimile Machines has 45
per cent, and a Hong Kong company, Champion Technology, 5.5 per cent. The
venture will have 800 employees, with a Chinese chairman and a Japanese
president.
The recent appreciation of the yen has encouraged Japanese companies to
locate an increasing share of their production facilities outside Japan so
as to take advantage of lower labour charges and to avoid yen-related costs.
China is a popular site because it offers lower costs and an rapidly growing
domestic market. Facsimile machines sales are expected to rise by 40 to 50
per cent annually until the end of the decade.
Mr Haruo Kamimoto, Ricoh's managing director, said the project is part of a
Beijing-approved programme to overhaul telecommunications infrastructure,
which should ensure that the venture has support.
