<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / UN closes Somali airstrips
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOGADISHU
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNITED NATIONS forces in Somalia yesterday closed two airfields to stop
supplies to fighters loyal to the fugitive warlord, General Mohammed Farah
Aideed, agencies report from Mogadishu.
Pakistani UN troops barricaded runways at an airfield 50km west of Mogadishu
and at second airstrip nearby. UN aircraft dropped thousands of leaflets
saying the airfields would be closed indefinitely.
A UN military spokesman, Major Dave Stockwell, said Gen Aideed's supporters
used the airfields to smuggle arms and shipments of khat, a narcotic plant
chewed by many Somalis. 'We know the Aideed faction obtains a good
proportion of its financing through importing and selling khat,' Maj
Stockwell said.
The UN action came two days after Somali gunmen killed four American UN
peacekeepers in an ambush. The closure appeared to be a first step towards a
new crackdown on Gen Aideed, blamed by the UN for Sunday's ambush.
</TEXT>
