FT  11 AUG 93 / Romanian coal strike ending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIRGINIA MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUCHAREST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A coal strike which has brought work to a standstill in the Jiu valley,
Romania's main deep mining region, looked to be winding down last night
after the government said union leaders had softened their pay demands,
writes Virginia Marsh in Bucharest.
A government official said the union was demanding wages ranging from 87,000
lei (Pounds 72) a month up to 281,000 lei (Pounds 233), including
supplements for night shift, overtime and dangerous work, compared to the
original demand for up to 320,000 lei (Pounds 266).
Discussions were continuing to see if the miners' proposals could be
reconciled with an offer of an average wage of 166,000 lei including
supplements from the RAH, the state-owned company which administers the
region's 13 mines.
