<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / German bid invited for Channel rail link contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government has privately invited a leading German contractor to form a
consortium and compete for the contract to build the Pounds 2bn-Pounds 3bn
high-speed rail link connecting the Channel tunnel with London.
Its approach to Hochtief - the Essen-based contractor responsible for
shifting the temples at Abu Simbel in Egypt and constructing the Bosporus
Bridge - is likely to annoy UK companies that have spent, in some cases,
millions of pounds in preliminary assessments.
The approach suggests the government is not happy with the companies which
have expressed interest in the project so far and is anxious to inject extra
competition into the bidding process. The government appears so eager to
transfer responsibility for the link to the private sector that it is ready
to award the work to continental European contractors with greater financial
muscle than their British counterparts. It is unclear whether soundings have
been made among other overseas groups.
The Department of Transport does not acknowledge the approach to Hochtief.
Officially, the government had made no 'proactive approaches' to individual
companies, the department said. But Hochtief confirmed it had been asked to
form a consortium. 'Of course, we are very interested,' it said.
Under the British Treasury's so-called Ryrie Rules, private sector finance
is allowed only if companies can prove that they can provide better value
for money than the public sector. This is not usually the case as the
government can borrow at lower rates of interest than the private sector.
The government's move will be seen by Eurorail, the Trafalgar House-GEC-BICC
joint venture established specifically to bid for the work on the link, as a
blow to its chances of success.
The chairman of a large construction company allied to the consortium said
he was 'spitting blood' about the Hochtief move.
In 1990, Eurorail's plan for an alternative link was turned down by the
transport secretary because the public subsidy required by the companies was
thought too high. In May this year GEC joined the largely British consortium
which is still fighting to win the contract.
The government issued a consultation paper earlier this year on how best to
harness the private sector for the project. The DoT this week appointed Hill
Samuel, the merchant bank, to co-ordinate the transfer of the project to the
private sector.
Funding gap 'threatens BR sell-off', Page 5
