<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / Karadzic threatens all-out war if Nato attacks Serbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOSNIAN SERB leader Mr Radovan Karadzic warned yesterday that Nato air
strikes against Serb targets could unleash an all-out war which would leave
his Moslem rivals with no territory.
'If a single bomb strikes a Serbian position, there would be no more talks.
We would have an all-out war and catastrophe,' he said. 'The attack would
trigger a huge battle and chaos. There would be tremendous suffering on all
three sides.'
Mr Karadzic added that he would probably lose control of Bosnian Serb
militiamen, apparently playing on the fears of Britain, France and Canada,
whose United Nations troops on the ground could face retaliation by Serb
forces.
His comments came in an interview after the international mediators, Lord
Owen and Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, postponed talks because Serb forces had
not withdrawn from strategic Mount Igman, west of Sarajevo.
French UN troops later said Bosnian Serb militiamen had retaken positions
they had vacated the previous day on mounts Igman and Bjelasnica - a move
that deepened international frustration about Serb manoeuvring. But as Nato
finalised its military preparations for possible strikes, after its meeting
on Monday which approved the logistics for strikes, officials admitted that
action was unlikely in the next couple of days.
Before any strikes can start, the UN, Nato or a member of the alliance must
make a specific appeal for action, which must then receive final
authorisation from Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN secretary-general.
US officials yesterday said they would be pushing for Mr Boutros Ghali to
approve action quickly, amid suspicions that the European allies still
lacked political will to press on with the strikes.
But speaking at his lakeside hotel in Geneva, Mr Karadzic denounced as
'absolutely irresponsible' western threats to launch air strikes. He said it
encouraged Bosnia's President Alija Izetbegovic to hold out for military
intervention and derail talks on the republic's ethnic partition.
Mr Izetbegovic has refused to return to the negotiating table with Serb and
Croat adversaries until Serb forces withdraw from the strategic heights
above Sarajevo.
He appears to be waiting to see whether Nato will push ahead with the air
strikes. He yesterday criticised Lord Owen for his cautious response to
Nato's threat. 'I am not satisfied with Owen's statement on air strikes. In
this way they (the mediators) are supporting the other side. This is counter
productive,' he said.
An angry Mr Karadzic warned: 'If Izetbegovic continues to sabotage the
talks, he will lose everything.'
Russia announced yesterday it was contacting the US and leaders in former
Yugoslavia to try to avert the use of outside force.
Russia has traditionally sympathised with the Serbs, although moderate
politicians around President Boris Yeltsin have been anxious not to let this
undermine improved relations with the west.
As a permanent member of the Security Council, Russia would have crucial
influence over whether air strikes should be authorised in Bosnia.
Letter, Page 12
</TEXT>
