<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / Liffe drops Globex talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LONDON International Financial Futures Exchange (Liffe), Europe's
largest derivatives exchange, has pulled out of negotiations to join Globex,
the after-hours electronic futures trading system.
The suspension of the year-long talks was described as 'mutually agreed'.
But the discussions were derailed two weeks ago when the Chicago Board of
Trade ruled that Liffe would not be able to list its successful German bond
contracts on the system.
'This does not bode well for Globex,' said one market participant. 'It shows
that the exchanges behind Globex are putting their own interests first.'
A year after the launch of Globex, France's Matif is the only futures
exchange to have listed its products on the system, which was jointly
developed by the CBOT, the Chicago Mercantile Exchange and Reuters, at an
estimated cost of Dollars 80m. The bulk of the 200,000 contracts traded so
far this month were Matif products.
Liffe had been given a list of the products which it would be allowed to
trade on Globex which included its Bund future contracts - its second most
actively traded product.
In a memo to CME members, Mr Jack Sandner reported that: 'On July 21, 1993,
the Chicago Boad of Trade instructed me, as Chairman of Globex, to inform
Liffe that Bund futures and options should be withdrawn from the list of
products available to Liffe.'
Mr Nick Durlacher, Liffe's chairman, described the decision to exclude the
Bund contracts as 'an insurmountable barrier' to Liffe joining Globex, even
though some other problems had been ironed out.
No senior CBOT officials were available to comment on the change of heart.
However, the CBOT gained approval from its regulator, the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission, to trade Bund and gilt futures several years ago.
Although these products have not yet been listed, the CBOT is believed to be
hoping to develop, and eventually list on Globex, its own Bund futures.
However, previous attempts by US exchanges to build up liquid markets in
European interest-rate products have not been successful.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
