<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / International Company News: Tandy disappoints with fall in
income
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TANDY Corporation, one of the largest US consumer electronics retailers and
manufacturers, yesterday disappointed Wall Street by reporting
second-quarter income from continuing operations of Dollars 31.7m, or 38
cents a share.
A year earlier, it recorded earnings from continuing operations of Dollars
42.7m, or 52 cents a share. Sales and revenues rose to Dollars 843.1m in the
1993 quarter from Dollars 801.9m last year.
Most analysts had expected the company to post profits of 43 cents a share
in the latest quarter, although some estimates were as low as 35 cents. At
the close in New York, shares in Tandy had fallen Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars
28 7/8 .
Tandy's results were muddied in both years by one-time items. In the 1993
quarter, it suffered a loss from discontinued operations of Dollars 109.1m.
A year earlier, one-time gains of Dollars 19m from the sale of a Japanese
subsidiary were partly offset by a loss from discontinued operations of
Dollars 14.6m.
Including these items, Tandy posted a second-quarter net loss of Dollars
77.3m, or Dollars 1.01, compared with net income of Dollars 28.1m, or 34
cents a year earlier.
For the first half, income from continuing operations slipped to Dollars
72.5m, or 88 cents, from Dollars 82m, or 97 cents the previous year.
