<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / International Company News: Dresdner Bank shows mid-term
improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LEIPZIG, FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DRESDNER BANK, Germany's second-largest commercial bank, yesterday reported
a 14 per cent rise in group operating profits to DM936m (Dollars 544.10m) in
the first half of this year after a big rise in loan risk provisions.
The result, from the last of the big three German banks to report interim
figures, is in line with the much-improved figures reported by its domestic
competitors.
Commerzbank's group operating result was 16 per cent higher at DM392m, while
Deutsche Bank showed a 13 per cent increase to DM2.6bn. Both the Dresdner
and Deutsche comparisons are with half of the full 1992 result rather than
with the calendar January - June period.
One reason for the banks' stronger performance during the recession is the
steep rise in commission income, reflecting stronger securities trading.
Despite the weaker economy and high German interest rates, Dresdner said
short and long-term lending had increased.
Operating profits at the Dresdner parent bank were 12 per cent higher at
DM661m. Provisions for bad loan risks, which German banks are now releasing
in more detail ahead of the implementation of a new EC banking directive,
rose by 25 per cent to DM758m for the group and by 27 per cent to DM554m for
the parent bank.
Business in eastern Germany, where economic progress after unification has
fallen well short of expectations, accounted for most of Dresdner's risk
provisions. But bank officials said that these had been strengthened because
of the continuing unsettled state of the domestic economy.
Dresdner's group lending volume rose by 4 per cent to DM250bn, with business
volume 8 per cent higher at DM359bn. The parent bank's own lending increased
by nearly 5 per cent to DM146bn, comprising a 5 per cent rise in the short
and medium-term sector and one of 3 per cent in long-term corporate
business.
</TEXT>
