<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / International Company News: Banesto share issues raise
Pta95bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANESTO, Spain's fourth-largest commercial bank in terms of assets, has
completed the first part of its plan to boost its capital and reserves,
raising Pta94.9bn (Dollars 676m) via two share issues.
This 37 per cent equity increase so far boosts its Bank of International
Settlements (BIS) equity ratio to 11.3 per cent of assets.
With an issue of convertible bonds still planned to round off the capital
increases in the autumn, Banesto has already raised more money than any
Spanish financial or commercial institution.
The success of the issues could help counter long-standing criticism of the
bank's ability to finance further growth.
Mr Mario Conde, Banesto's president, said yesterday that the Pta94.9bn was
the third-largest capital increase by any bank in the world and that it
would be the biggest when at least Dollars 400m in dollar-denominated
convertible bonds was issued in late September.
He said that the two share issues, the first part of the overall capital
increase, had proved popular with Banesto shareholders and that the first
tranche of the money raised so far - Pta52.65bn - was oversubscribed by 20
per cent. A second tranche of Pta42.25bn was then used to attract a series
of private European and US investors.
The most prominent of these was the Corsair banking fund launched by JP
Morgan earlier this year, which invested Dollars 150m and, after the share
issues, holds a stake of around 6.4 per cent in Banesto.
At least two members of the Corsair funds, the GE pension fund and
Northwestern Mutual, a big Milwaukee-based insurer, also made individual
investments.
Mr Conde invested Dollars 50m, and said the money had come from his personal
funds. His own stake in the bank is close to 3 per cent. Other Banesto board
members invested Dollars 20m.
With net profits of more than Pta20bn from the sale earlier this year of its
Banco Madrid affiliate to Deutsche Bank, the capital increase removes any
doubts about Banesto's ability to finance its growth.
Mr Conde made clear he will continue disposing of assets in Banesto's
industrial holdings but that in the current business climate prices were not
good.
He said, though, that the implementation of the capital increase so far had
also made it very clear that Banesto's banking business was rapidly
improving.
Acting in the first tranche of the increase, its Spanish branch network
raised Pta18.2bn from existing shareholders and Pta19.7bn from more than
37,000 customers who had become shareholders through the exercise.
</TEXT>
