<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 93 / International Company News: Procter &amp; Gamble hit by
provisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE costs of the restructuring programme announced by Procter &amp; Gamble last
month, and some other large one-off charges, took the Cincinnati-based
consumer products group heavily into the red in the 12 months to end-June.
P&amp;G said yesterday that it made an after-tax loss of Dollars 656m in its
latest financial year. Sales were Dollars 30.4bn, up 3.6 per cent.
However, the deficit was due solely to P&amp;G's previously-announced Dollars
1.5bn after-tax reserve, designed to fund the cost-cutting moves announced
in mid-July, and a further Dollars 1bn non-cash charge to cover the new
accounting standards on retiree medical benefits and deferred taxes. Added
to a Dollars 200m restructuring provision, established last September to
cover the disposal of P&amp;G's fruit juice business, one-off charges reduced
P&amp;G's profits last year by Dollars 2.7bn.
Before these charges, P&amp;G said that after-tax earnings wereDollars 2.07bn,
11 per cent up on the Dollars 1.87bn of the previous year. Earnings per
share, ahead of charges, stood at Dollars 2.91, also up by 11 per cent.
In the fourth quarter, P&amp;G's after-tax profits - before the charges -
increased by just 1 per cent, to Dollars 341m, while sales increased by 3
per cent to Dollars 7.36bn. However, Mr Edwin Artzt, chairman, noted that
pre-tax operating profits showed a more healthy 9 per cent increase.
In the US, underlying unit volume increased by 1 per cent during the year
overall, although by 6 per cent in the final quarter. The international
businesses saw a 10 per cent increase in unit volume during 1992-3.
