<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Unisys president quits in shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNISYS, the US-based mainframe computer company which broke back into profit
last year, yesterday announced an organisational shake-up to give more
autonomy to its two fastest-growing business units.
The shake-up also resulted in the resignation of Mr Reto Braun, president
and chief operating officer.
Mr James Unruh, chairman, said: 'The intention was to flatten the corporate
structure. We eliminated the need for a chief operating officer function.'
The two businesses being given greater operational freedom cover consulting
services, and the provision of open systems. Together, they accounted for 29
per cent of the company's Dollars 8.4bn (Pounds 5.6bn) sales in 1992.
'We're trying to achieve the advantages specialised companies have, without
losing the advantages of economy of scale and the breadth of market of large
companies,' Mr Unruh said.
He added that the move was not a prelude to the eventual hiving-off of the
two units, though he added: 'Ten years from now, the company will no doubt
look very different.'
The two units will have full control over their businesses, and will have
their own dedicated sales forces around the world.
Unisys also said that its business was being regrouped into three broad
divisions. These cover government systems, combining the former government
and defence systems groups; information services and systems, which includes
the three sales groups around the world and four product groups aimed at
different industry sectors; and computer systems, which would continue to
act as the mainframe manufacturing arm.
With the departure of Mr Braun, Mr Unruh said he was taking day-to-day
control of the information group, the largest of the three.
Unisys, created by the merger of the Burroughs and Sperry mainframe computer
businesses in 1986, experienced heavy losses from 1988 to 1991. Cost-cutting
had taken 'at least Dollars 1bn' out of the company's cost base since then,
Mr Unruh said.
He called yesterday's changes the second phase of Unisys's rehabilitation,
designed to boost income by making it more responsive to market
developments.
In a separate announcement, Moore Corporation, a Toronto-based business form
group, said that Mr Braun would be joining as chief executive at the
beginning of September.
</TEXT>
