<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Tokyo stock prices rise as LDP defectors dominate new
cabinet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S new prime minister, Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, the head of a seven
party-coalition, yesterday unveiled a conservative cabinet which promised to
maintain foreign and economic policies generally in line with those of the
outgoing Liberal Democratic party.
Mr Hosokawa insisted his 20-person cabinet reflected a 'new era' in
politics, citing the appointment of three women, one more than the previous
record, two people without party political affiliations, and representatives
from a range of parties, including the Social Democratic party, formerly the
Japan Socialist party. 'We should continue what should be continued and
renew what should be renewed,' Mr Hosokawa said. 'We have promised to reform
Japanese politics, and we want to fulfil the people's expectations for
change.'
However, the influence of LDP defectors, who took the leading posts of
finance, trade and industry, agriculture, defence and foreign affairs,
prompted Japanese newspapers to dub the selection the 'Ozawa cabinet' in
honour of Mr Ichiro Ozawa, the former LDP powerbroker, now pulling strings
inside the coalition.
Tokyo stock prices rose after the announcement of the cabinet, which allayed
fears that the new government would confront the powerful bureaucracy over
economic policy. The new finance minister, Mr Hirohisa Fujii, is a former
Finance Ministry official.
Mr Fujii, 61, who has worked for the ministry's budget bureau, said the
government would consider new stimulatory measures for a still slowing
economy, but would not embark on a spending spree. 'We have no intention of
using deficit-covering bonds to increase spending,' he said.
The new opposition leader, Mr Yohei Kono, the LDP president, complained that
he could see little difference between the new government's policies and
those of the LDP, which had ruled for 38 years until last week.
'I noticed that some of the new ministers appeared to be reading from notes
prepared by bureaucrats. I think the public would have preferred them to do
some things differently,' he said.
The choice of Mr Tsutomu Hata, 57, as deputy prime minister and foreign
minister completes a circle for the man who turned down the foreign
minister's post not long before defecting from the LDP this year, saying his
priority was political reform.
The cabinet's stated policy priority is to change the electoral system
within a year.
Details of new Cabinet
Likely policy changes assessed
Hata: the lone elder statesman, Page 3
