<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Performance pay deal could give top civil servants 3.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOP CIVIL servants could win pay increases this year averaging 3.5 per cent
 -more than double the government's 1.5 per cent public sector pay limit -
under a performance pay arrangement offered by the Treasury.
Members of the Association of First Division Civil Servants (FDA) are
currently being balloted on the offer, which affects more than 10,000 civil
servants in grades seven to five (principals to assistant secretaries).
The offer is similar to the deal agreed earlier this year with more than
100,000 white-collar civil servants.
Such deals do not formally breach the government's public sector pay ceiling
because the Treasury agreed last year that money previously used for annual
increments would in the future be used for performance-related pay.
Annual increments, which are enjoyed by a large percentage of public sector
workers, including civil servants and nurses, are excluded from the 1.5 per
cent pay limit.
However, Unison, the new 1.4m-strong public sector union, which represents
large numbers of workers who do not get an-nual increments, said it was
'inconsistent and unfair' that civil servants were treated differently from
other public sector workers.
A spokeswoman for the union, formed from a merger of the Nalgo, Nupe and
Cohse public service unions in June, said that workers such as firefighters
and ambulance workers, who are balloting on strike action in protest at the
1.5 per cent limit, had not been offered a similar deal.
Senior civil servants have been offered a 1.25 per cent increase for
inflation plus a further 2.25 per cent which in the past would have been
used for annual increments.
If the offer is accepted, government departments will be free to decide
whether to award a total of 3.5 per cent for performance or to provide a
standard increase of 1.25 per cent, with the rest used to reward
performance.
The FDA said that the total pay bill for their members would only increase
by 1.25 per cent because the increments were traditionally self fin-ancing.
The government has indicated that while there must be no 'catch-up' on
public sector pay after this year's 1.5 per cent limit, there will be a more
flexible approach in 1994-95.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
