<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Third of employers insist on overtime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE THIRD of companies insist employees should work overtime, according to a
survey published by Industrial Relations Services.
But more than half the companies in the study said they had recently
introduced measures to restrict overtime, including shift work, extra staff
and tighter management control. However, only five of the 65 companies in
the survey set limits on the amount of overtime worked by an employee. The
amount of overtime being worked was similar to last year, with five out of
six companies reporting levels of overtime 'currently the same or lower than
last year'.
According to the survey, St Regis Paper said it restricted overtime in one
week to 28 hours, while Scottish Amicable Life Assurance said it limited
overtime to 24 hours a month.
Suttons Seeds said overtime in the company had to be approved by the
directors. Calor Gas and PPG Industries (glass fibre division) said they
employed temporary or contract staff as a way of reducing dependence on
overtime.
Both PLM Redfearn, a packaging company, and Premier Fabrics said they had
recruited more staff to cut overtime.
Few companies have altered their methods of calculating overtime pay in the
past five years, with little difference between manufacturing and service
sectors. The most common rate for overtime pay is time and a half on
weekdays and Saturday, double time on Sunday and double time plus time off
on public holidays.
The overtime rate is calculated as a fraction of a worker's normal hourly
rate and then added to the hourly rate. The median overtime hours worked in
the survey amounted to four a week but on average 20 extra hours were worked
at Tate and Lyle.
Overtime pay remains predominantly a blue-collar worker phenomenon. A third
of respondents said overtime entitlements stopped at supervisory level while
another third used the lower level of management as the cut-off point.
London Underground, Woolwich building society and John Brown Engineering
said overtime working extended to at least some of their middle management.
Industrial Relations Review and Report No 541 August. 18-20 Highbury Place,
London N5 1QP.
</TEXT>
