<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow at record high after
budget victory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices surged to record highs yesterday after bond yields dropped
sharply in reaction to President Clinton's budget victory, writes Patrick
Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 15.65 at 3,576.08,
above its previous record close of 3,567.42 but below its highs for the day.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended up 2.03 at 450.71, while
the Amex composite finished 2.46 higher at 438.80, and the Nasdaq composite
up 0.41 at 718.49, a new all-time high. Trading volume on the NYSE was 232m
shares.
Prices opened firmer, but did not post strong gains until mid-morning when
the bond market's latest rally took hold. Bond prices rose sharply, and sent
the yield on the benchmark 30-year issue below 6.5 per cent for the first
time, as fixed-income investors applauded the Senate's approval last Friday
of President Clinton's deficit-reduction package.
The bond rally surprised dealers and investors, who did not expect much
reaction to the Senate vote because approval of the budget had already been
priced into Treasuries. The big drop in yields, however, was welcomed by the
stock markets, and with computerised program buying adding to the upward
momentum, prices raced to new highs just before midday.
Among individual stocks, interest rate-sensitive issues in the financials
sector fared well, with brokerage companies leading the way. Salomon climbed
Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 44 5/8 , Merrill Lynch added Dollars  3/4 at
Dollars 89 1/4 , Primerica rose Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 56 5/8 , Morgan
Stanley firmed Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 73 1/8 and Bear Stearns put on
Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 24 3/8 .
Motor company stocks were in demand. The sector has been in favour recently
following strong quarterly earnings reports, but last Friday it ran into
profit-taking, suffering heavy losses. Yesterday, the sector rallied, with
General Motors adding Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 49, Ford putting on Dollars
5/8 at Dollars 52 1/4 and Chrysler climbing Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 43 1/4
. Selected drug stocks weakened following downgrades from the investment
bank, Lehman Brothers. Schering-Plough fell Dollars 2 to Dollars 59 3/8 ,
Johnson &amp; Johnson dropped Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 36 7/8 and Bristol-Myers
Squibb gave up Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 51 5/8 .
Eastman Kodak continued to rally in the wake of last week's ousting of its
chairman, Mr Kay Whitmore, rising another Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 59 7/8 .
On the Nasdaq market, Sun Microsystems fell Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 28 1/4
after the National Security Agency suspended a Dollars 200m workstation
contract with the company after competitors said that the machine's
performance was misrepresented.
Canada
TORONTO closed higher, led by recovering gold stocks. The composite index
rose 42.24 to close at 4,002.20 in turnover of CDollars 510.3m. Advances led
declines by 390 to 292. Volume was 42.8m shares.
The gold sub-index rose 4.5 per cent as the gold price rebounded from last
week's fall. Ten of the other 13 sub-indexes also closed higher.
Among gold stocks, Franco-Nevada soared CDollars 3 5/8 to CDollars 71 5/8 ,
American Barrick jumped CDollars 1 3/8 to CDollars 33 1/8 , and Placer Dome
gained CDollars 1 to CDollars 26 3/8 .
</TEXT>
