<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Money Markets: French futures tumble
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRENCH interest rate futures tumbled yesterday after the Bank of France
disappointed dealers by only reducing the cost of overnight funds by a 1/4
of a percentage point, writes James Blitz.
Yesterday's easing in monetary policy was the first since the widening of
the exchange rate mechanism's bands more than a week ago. But the scale of
the move, which pushed the cost of overnight money down to 9.75 per cent,
gave the impression that France is still trying to hang on to the D-Mark's
coat-tails in the ERM, and that rates will come down slowly.
The Bank of France's strategy failed to impress money market dealers. The
franc dropped nearly 2 centimes, underlining that tight monetary policy is
not credible as far as the markets are concerned. The Bank also added
FFr18.9bn to the money market in its domestic tender, too small a sum to
bring cash rates down by much.
Three month French francs closed more-or-less unchanged by the end of the
day at 8 per cent. The September French franc contract dropped 40 basis
points, from a high of 93.50 at the start of the day to close at 93.10.
Interest rate futures dealers took the view that German rates will be about
 1/2 percentage point lower than French rates in two months time. It is only
in December that futures dealers are discounting lower rates in France than
Germany.
Euromarks were nevertheless a touch lower yesterday after Mr Johann Wilhelm
Gaddum, the Bundesbank's vice-president, said at the weekend that dealers
could not expect big cuts in interest rates in the next few months. The
September Euromark contract was down 6 basis points at 93.51. There were
expectations that the Bundesbank would again hold a fixed rate repo at 6.80
per cent for 14 day maturities, only 5 basis points above the Discount rate
level.
The downbeat atmosphere affected sterling markets where the September
sterling contract fell 9 basis points to close at 94.16. Rates in the cash
market were kept high by difficulties removing a large Pounds 1.85bn
shortage. There was Pounds 730m of late assistance and the overnight rate
was as high as 11 per cent at one stage. Three month money was slightly
lower at 5.70 per cent from 5.75 per cent earlier in the day.
</TEXT>
