<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / International Company News: May stores climbs to Dollars
117m in real terms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MAY Department Stores, one of the largest department store operators in the
US, yesterday reported an underlying 22 per cent increase in second-quarter
earnings per share, at 44 cents, in the three months to end-July.
May's actual after-tax profits for the period fell from Dollars 393m to
Dollars 117m, but the 1992 results were boosted by a one-off gain of Dollars
298m pre-tax.
Had this been excluded, May said second-quarter after-tax profits would have
risen from Dollars 95m to Dollars 117m year-on-year.
May's sales overall rose from Dollars 2.31bn to Dollars 2.5bn, with Dollars
513m, against Dollars 452m, coming from the Payless ShoeSource division, and
Dollars 1.99bn, compared with Dollars 1.86bn, from the department stores.
During the quarter, May opened a new Kaufmann's department store in
Syracuse, New York, and a net 70 new Payless shoe stores.
May, which recently outlined wide-ranging expansion plans, said it would
open another 11 department stores during the remainder of 1993, and add
about 150 Payless outlets by the end of its current financial year.
The second-quarter results mean May's after-tax profits for the first half
of the year stand at Dollars 213m, with sales rising to Dollars 4.82bn from
Dollars 4.51bn.
</TEXT>
