<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / International Company News: Barlow Rand to split into four
parts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BARLOW Rand, South Africa's largest industrial company, has announced
details of a corporate restructuring which will see the group broken up into
four separate parts.
The announcement comes a week after Gencor, the country's second-largest
mining house, announced details of plans to break up the group.
It is not, however, expected to herald an unbundling trend among the
country's big groups. Anglo American and Rembrandt, two of the largest
conglomerates, have both said they have no such plans.
Although there are political pressures, notably from the ANC, for the big
groups to unbundle, there is no indication that this was a factor in
Barlow's decision.
Key points in the plan are:
The rump of Barlow will include a 79 per cent holding in J Bibby &amp; Sons, the
group's offshore arm, a 60 per cent holding in Pretoria Portland Cement, and
wholly-owned businesses ranging from domestic appliances to capital
equipment;
CG Smith, which will have a consumer focus, and include the group's food,
pharmaceutical, packaging, and textiles interests;
Reunert, which will focus on electronics and information technology;
Rand Mines, whose main asset is a 71 per cent stake in Randcoal, one of the
country's main coal houses, and Rand Mines Properties (RMP).
Existing Barlow shareholders will receive separate shares in CG Smith,
Reunert, Rand Mines and RMP.
To repay debt and build up funds after its reconstitution, Barlow will raise
R607m (Dollars 180m) by selling 7.5 per cent of the share capital of CG
Smith, Reunert, Rand Mines and RMP shares, to Old Mutual, its largest
shareholder.
A detailed announcement will be made by September 30 and the implementation
of the proposals should be completed by the end of February 1994.
</TEXT>
