<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The four-part series on Genghis Khan and the Mongol empire, Storm From The
East which begins today (9.45) was made after Japan's main broadcaster, NHK,
approached the BBC. The Japanese and the British, we are told, found that
there were 'significant differences in emphasis' in what they wanted to say.
BBC producer Robert Marshall claims 'The Japanese find it very difficult to
be critical about anyone, even Genghis Khan'. So the two scripts differed:
'The BBC's goes into detail on the conquests and massive slaughter involved
while the Japanese concentrate more on anthropology and the countryside'.
The mind boggles.
The shift towards real-life crime as entertainment continues rapidly. Inside
Crime is yet another series which promises to combine analysis with 'reconst
ructions'. Today's opening episode (7.30 ITV) will reconstruct the mugging
of Frederick Carter who died a week after being attacked in a lift. Won't
that be nice.
In Far Flung Floyd the leader of the gastronauts moves on to West Malaysia
(8.30 BBC2).
