<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Euro-constituency plans announced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday announced the procedures it will use to redraw the
electoral boundaries of England and Wales for next year's elections to the
European parliament.
The addition of an extra five constituencies in England, and one for Wales,
which followed a deal at last year's Edinburgh summit to compensate for the
addition of 18 new seats in eastern Germany, required extensive alterations
to the electoral map. Public consultation will now be carried out very
quickly.
The Committee for England, appointed by Mr Michael Howard, the home
secretary, proposes to publish its provisional recommendations for European
constituencies on September 22. Representations for or against these
recommendations and counter-proposals will need to be submitted to the
committee by October 22.
These will then be deposited in each district council area by November 8,
and any responses will have to be submitted by November 24.
The government said: 'The timetable in the bill does not permit the
committee to hold local inquiries. The timetable is tight because of the
requirement in the bill to report 'as soon as practicable' and also because
the next European parliamentary elections are to be held in June 1994.'
However, the committee is confident that it can make final recommendations
to the home secretary by Christmas. It added that it was 'aware that the
tightness of the intended timetable outlined may cause problems for local
authorities and other organisations. The timetable is unavoidable'.
Some Conservatives have complained about the timetable and Labour has
criticised the plans for not involving the independent Boundary Commission,
which is responsible for setting constituencies for the UK parliament.
Commission members will advise the committee.
Under the rules, each European constituency must include two or more
parliamentary constituencies, and no parliamentary constituency will be
split between two European constituencies. The total electorate in each case
will be as close as possible to an average figure of 512,851.
</TEXT>
