<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Harrods rebuffs prison's cheese
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUST AS THE government's programme to involve the private sector in
Britain's prisons had recovered from jokes about prisoners escaping when
transported by security companies, it yesterday ran into another potential
embarrassment. About cheese.
Mr Derek Lewis, director-general of the Prison Service, last week launched
an innovative scheme at East Sutton Park prison, Kent, where women inmates
have been trained in cheesemaking.
They are producing mozzarella and ricotta which will be marketed by Mr
Edgardo Pasquali, a private-sector partner of the Prison Service, through
his company Mama Mia.
At the inauguration of the scheme Mr Pasquali said products would go to
'only the best' outlets, including many leading London stores, hotels and
restaurants.
But Harrods, one of the up-market outlets named by Mr Pasquali, asserted
yesterday: 'We do not stock this cheese and it is unlikely that we will do
so.'
Mr Pasquali, whose enthusiasm for the quality of the cheese being produced
by the prisoners is evident, remained convinced yesterday that few suppliers
will be able to resist stocking it. But he admitted that it remained a
matter for negotiation.
Mr Pietro Pesce, whose company Danmar has been asked to handle the
distribution of the cheeses in central London, said yesterday that he had
just returned from holiday and had not yet discussed final arrangements with
Mr Pasquali.
Mr Pesce said: 'Harrods and many other leading London outlets are customers
of ours, and are the sort of suppliers we would offer the cheese to. It is a
good, locally produced product and I am sure they would wish to consider it.
But obviously we cannot force any customer to take a particular product.'
The Prison Service says many checks were made before it entered into the
partnership. 'We are satisfied that the product is good and the venture is a
sound one,' it said.
One of the intentions of the project is to help prepare prisoners for future
employment. Yesterday's developments suggest that skills learned on the
scheme might extend far beyond cheesemaking into the complex world of
negotiations between producers, distributors, retailers and public and
private-sector partners.
