FT  10 AUG 93 / VSEL in limited offer to Swans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VSEL, the Barrow-in-Furness naval shipbuilder, has offered to take over the
management of shipbuilding at its troubled Tyneside rival Swan Hunter,
Daniel Green writes.
VSEL, which in May won a competition against Swans to build a helicopter
carrier for the Ministry of Defence, wants to manage Swans' work on three
Type 23 Navy frigates.
Mr Noel Davies, chief executive of VSEL, said: 'Under no circumstances are
we interested in all of Swan Hunter. We are interested in certain assets and
in the possibility of managing the completion of the three frigates.'
Swans went into receivership in May after it lost the helicopter carrier
contract. Price Waterhouse, the receiver, said yesterday that it would not
yet accept an offer that did not mean the sale of all or 'a substantial
part' of the yard.
VSEL approached Price Waterhouse shortly after its appointment as receiver
and had been hoping for a clear response by now. Details of other offers for
all or part of Swans may be announced this morning at a creditors' meeting.
Swans won the frigate contract in 1989 against bids from other naval
shipyards including Cammell Laird, owned by VSEL. The contract should
provide work until November next year and improves the prospects of the yard
being sold as a going concern.
