<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Companies look to their futures: Forex hedging has a new
urgency after the ERM tremors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN and CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGING foreign-exchange risk 'has become more complicated, more
time-consuming and the costs have gone up. We have to fiddle round with bits
of minor currencies. It diverts valuable time from doing deals.'
This litany of complaints about the effective collapse of the European
exchange rate mechanism comes from Mr Rusi Kathoke, finance director of
British Technology Group, which licenses technology around the world.
But it could have come from any small or medium-sized British company coping
with the new currency regime.
Smaller companies are not alone in suffering from currency uncertainty, but
they are less likely than large ones to have the staff and the expertise to
deal with it. They are also more likely to trade only within Europe, and
therefore to have relied on the ERM to protect them from volatility in
currencies.
'Larger companies have been hedging currencies for some while,' said Mr
Robert Mapstone, a derivatives specialist at NatWest Capital Markets.
However, the surge of volatility in the currency markets last summer,
culminating in sterling's departure from the ERM in September, sparked a
fresh wave of interest in hedging foreign-exchange risk.
'There has been a trend towards increased use of derivative instruments
(futures and options contracts),' said Mr Geoffrey Isaac, chairman of MTM
Partnership, a financial strategy consultancy.
However, some companies only use forward foreign-exchange contracts, which
involve buying a currency at a set rate in advance, rather than options,
which give the holder an option to buy a currency at a set rate at a set
time. This is because some companies consider forward contracts a cheaper
and sometimes less risky form of hedging. But unlike forward contracts,
buying an option does not lock a company into a potentially unfavourable
exchange rate.
Most large companies said there had been no change of policy following the
ERM shake-up just over a week ago.
'We haven't seen the risks we run as being changed, but the adoption of
wider bands may focus the attention of some companies (on foreign-exchange
risk),' said Mr John Grout, director of treasury at Cadbury Schweppes, the
food and drinks group. Cadbury already makes extensive use of options to
hedge its exposure to foreign-exchange risk, mainly dollars and D-Marks.
Guinness, the drinks group, is also active in hedging its currency exposure.
It said there had been no action because the company's exposure is already
hedged well into next year.
Hedging has become a necessity rather than a choice even for companies which
in the past have steered clear of the derivatives market. They feared
repeating the experience of Allied-Lyons, the food and drinks group, which
two years ago lost Pounds 150m from writing currency options.
Companies are taking what Mr Christopher Taylor, head of foreign exchange
and money markets at Barclays, sees as 'a more enlightened approach' to
derivative instruments.
But he says it is not only large companies which are active in hedging
exposure: 'In many cases it's the small-to-medium-sized companies which have
been more active because they have shorter management chains: one of the
barriers in larger companies is the need for senior management approval.'
Designers Guild, a designer and manufacturer of fabrics and wallpapers based
in west London, recently decided to take out forward contracts to cover 60
per cent of its foreign currency exposure. 'I wish now I had taken out 100
per cent cover,' said Mr Mark Naughton-Rumbo, financial controller. The
company exports more than 60 per cent of its annual turnover of Pounds 18m.
It has also had to allocate one staff member to compile a report each
morning on the company's foreign-exchange exposure. 'The foreign-exchange
position can change overnight,' said Mr Naughton-Rumbo. 'We could not afford
to take a Pounds 50,000 foreign currency loss.'
But for some, the worst impact of the volatility in currencies has been the
damage it had done to business confidence throughout Europe. 'The level of
uncertainty won't help us out of the recession,' remarked Mr Naughton-Rumbo.
Suppliers of machinery and other capital equipment, with long lead times
between the order and delivery, face particular difficulties. 'How can I
quote a price to a customer in France when it takes two to three months
until delivery?' said Mr Fred Marshall, managing director of Speedex
(Engineering), a Bradford-based manufacturer of plastics extrusion machinery
with annual sales of nearly Pounds 3m.
He added: 'When I talk to my customers it is not about the technicalities of
our machines but about currencies. I can't understand the sense of allowing
gamblers, people who don't manufacture, to dictate what a currency is worth.
The ideal would be for one currency.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
