<DOCNO>FT933-9479</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DHJCNABTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930810
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Qatar to contest tribunal's Pounds 385m award to Westland
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
QATAR is to contest the ruling last month by a Geneva-based arbitration
tribunal that it, along with two other Arab governments, owes the British
helicopter company Westland Pounds 385m in an action for breach of contract.
Last month the tribunal awarded Westland the money in damages in the
company's action against the governments of Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the
United Arab Emirates, as well as the Arab Organisation for Industrialisation
and the Arab British Helicopter Company.
A statement carried by the Qatari News Agency yesterday said the tribunal
'has no jurisdiction over any of the three countries, and any ruling by it
does not bind any of these countries to pay any amount of money to
Westland'.
The dispute, which has been continuing since 1980 in the International
Chamber of Commerce, concerns the collapse of an Egyptian-based helicopter
manufacturing project.
The tribunal decided in Westland's favour two years ago, ruling that the
industrialisation body and the three states were liable for damages for
breach of contract. The sum owed was set last month.
The project, launched in 1978, involved setting up manufacturing facilities
in Egypt for Westland Lynx military helicopters. It was to be done through
Arab British Helicopter, a joint venture with the industrialisation body,
Egypt and the three Gulf states.
The partnership broke up after the 1979 Israel-Egypt peace treaty and the
subsequent ostracism of Egypt by other Arab governments, leaving Westland
stranded after investing in the new facility.
The four partner countries were to have bought the first 250 helicopters
produced at the plant, with further production intended for export.
</TEXT>
