<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / Stamp fraud 'costs millions'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
STAMP fraudsters are costing the Post Office millions of pounds a year by
selling fake stamps and 'washed' stamps - used stamps with the postmark
removed - the government said yesterday.
In a letter to Mr Tam Dalyell, the Labour MP for Linlithgow, Mr Patrick
McLoughlin, the junior trade and industry minister, said: 'It is difficult
to judge the scale . . . but I'm told it could well run into millions of
pounds a year.'
The biggest single recent case was in 1989, when Post Office investigators
found sacks containing Pounds 10m of used stamps. The fraud involved dealers
buying used stamps from charities, chemically 'washing' them and selling
them - mainly as mint unfranked examples to collectors, although some were
believed to have been resold for general use. About 60 people have been
arrested since April 1991 for stamp offences.
Mr McLoughlin said: 'There is little hope of eradicating this problem
entirely,' and the Post Office said there had never been a precise estimate
of the level of potential fraud.
</TEXT>
