<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 93 / World Trade News: Ministers break off talks on Nafta's
supplementary pacts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS from the US, Canada and Mexico yesterday suddenly broke off 10
days of talks on side agreements to the North American Free Trade Agreement
in Washington.
They left strong doubts that they can complete a deal in time to implement
the pact on schedule next January.
The ministers stated there was 'a handful of remaining issues. Officials
will continue to work this week in order to address these issues.'
Who those officials are remained a mystery. Mr Rufus Yerxa, US deputy trade
representative, was seen leaving for vacation in a van with his family. Mr
Mickey Kantor, US Trade Representative, let it be known that he plans to
leave for his vacation on Friday.
Mr Thomas Hockin, Canada's trade minister, was to leave yesterday for a
cabinet meeting in Ottawa. Officials of Canada, the US and Mexico denied
that the latter two countries were negotiating separate deals in the talks
over environment, labour, import surges and financing of a US-Mexico border
clean-up.
Canada has been a firm opponent of a US proposal to create a strong
enforcement mechanism if any of the three governments were to fail to
enforce its labour or environmental laws. Mexico has backed a proposal to
use the levying of fines for enforcement, but this has been blocked by
Democrats in the US Congress.
At the very least, the US and Mexico are expected to agree to some
combination of fines and tariff 'snapbacks' in the event of 'persistent,
systematic and unjustifiable' non-enforcement of environmental laws.
In Congress, there is much concern that fighting over Nafta has 'turned
intensely ugly.' US corporations, hostile to labour and environmental
enforcement, are believed to be supplying Mexico with proposals to bring to
the bargaining.
Ms Lori Wallach, a lawyer of Public Citizen, a citizens' group opposed to
Nafta, predicted there would be 'teeth' in the final agreement over
sanctions to enforce labour and environment agreements, as the Clinton
administration has often promised, but teeth at the end of 'a long, twisted,
tortuous' process of dispute settlement.
Mr Kantor has made little progress in satisfying Ms Wallach and other
opponents of the pact. Disputes between the US and Mexico over the
environment can drag on for years, critics say, because there are no precise
deadlines for investigations and settlement, unlike commercial disputes.
</TEXT>
